article.description:
Jason Richardson scored 31 points and the Golden
State Warriors broke open a close game early in the fourth quarter
to hand the Boston Celtics their sixth straight loss, 107-95
Wednesday night.
article.headline: Golden State sends Boston to sixth straight loss
article.linkText: Richardson, Warriors add to Celtics' woes
article.story:
BOSTON (AP) -- The Golden State Warriors took out their frustrations from a damaging loss on the slumping Boston Celtics.
 
Richardson
Jason Richardson scored 31 points in a 107-95 win over the Celtics on Wednesday night, one day after the Warriors lost by 21 points to the team with the NBA's worst record -- the Cleveland Cavaliers. "That was a devastating way to start our road trip," Golden State coach Eric Musselman said. "We had a team meeting and the team seemed focused." It took nearly three quarters before the Warriors broke open a close game, but they broke it open in a big way. Golden State built a 22-point lead midway through the fourth before the Celtics, who lost their season-high sixth straight game, scored the last eight. Boston remained in sixth place in the East. The Warriors, with 10 games left, have an outside shot at a playoff berth in the tougher Western Conference. "If we were in the East, we'd be right in the playoff race," Richardson said. "We talk about that all the time." Richardson added seven assists as the Warriors, the league's third-highest scoring team, got big games from four starters. Antawn Jamison had 29 points, including 15 in the third quarter, and seven rebounds, Gilbert Arenas added 23 points, 10 assists and seven rebounds and Troy Murphy finished with 18 points and 11 rebounds. With 52 percent shooting and a 48-35 rebounding advantage, it didn't hurt the Warriors to get just six points from the rest of their team. "You have to make shots in order to beat a team like that because they're going to make you score a lot of points," Boston coach Jim O'Brien said. But the Celtics shot only 15-of-44 in the second half, 34 percent, after sinking 53 percent in the first half, which ended with the score tied at 55. Paul Pierce had 25 points and Eric Williams 15 for the Celtics. "We fought for two or three quarters, then the fight was over with," Pierce said. The Warriors took an 81-74 lead at the end of the third quarter on a driving layup by Arenas -- who then slammed the ball off the floor. Antoine Walker protested that Arenas should get a technical foul, and referee Dan Crawford assessed one to both Arenas and Walker. Things kept getting worse for the Celtics after that. The Warriors opened the fourth quarter with a 20-5 run that made it 101-79, their biggest lead, with 5:35 remaining. "This was the best time for us to get them" during a losing streak, Arenas said. "Once we blew open the lead, you could see them hanging their heads." Murphy and Williams traded baskets at the start of the surge before Murphy hit a jumper and Arenas sank a 3-pointer, making it 88-76. Pierce then made a free throw before Golden State got the next eight points on 3-pointers by Arenas and Richardson and a layup by Jamison that gave the Warriors a 96-77 lead with 7:29 to play. Walker's layup broke the run, but Richardson followed with a layup and Arenas hit another 3-pointer as the lead grew to 101-79. "Every team in the East has gone through" a losing streak, Walker said. "It's just unfortunate that ours came now." There were 15 lead changes in the first half and neither team led by more than four points until Murphy's free throw made it 71-66 with 6:13 left in the third quarter. Game notes
The Celtics played without two of their top eight players. Starting C Tony Battie had a sore left knee and G Tony Delk missed the game because of his father's death. ... In their other meeting this season, the Celtics reached their season high for points in a 125-117 win over the Warriors. ... Jamison made his 237th straight start, the second longest among active players behind Utah's John Stockton. ... The Warriors are 5-5 in their last 10 games, never getting two wins or two losses in a row.
